-- digdata.lua -- the chocobo-digging database, to be GENERATED by
-- tools/gen_digdata.py from the CatsEyeXI server's chocobo-digging data
-- (following the gen_petmods.py / gen_zones.py pattern). Do not hand-edit the
-- generated sections; rebuild with:
--   python tools/gen_digdata.py      (maintainer only, ships with updates)
-- Loaded lazily and fails soft (feature/digcalc.lua M.db) -- a missing or
-- partial table disables the data-backed queries, never errors.
--
-- ===========================================================================
-- !! DATA STATUS (issue #94) !!  The per-zone loot pools below (`zones`) are
-- the CatsEyeXI-SPECIFIC part of the data: the 26 enabled digging zones, each
-- item's dig weight and rank requirement, grouped by pool. Those numbers live
-- ONLY in the server's private chocobo-digging source and MUST be populated by
-- running gen_digdata.py against that checkout (maintainer-only) BEFORE the
-- digging guide ships. Until then `zones` is empty and every by-zone query
-- fails soft. The odds engine (digcalc) is fully implemented and tested against
-- hand-computed pools independent of this table; the conditional rule tables
-- below are FFXI-standard and complete. See the PR for #94 for the hand-over.
-- ===========================================================================
--
-- Shapes (docs/design/chocobo-dig.md, PRD #93 / issue #94):
--   zones[zoneId] = { n = "Zone Name", pools = { <Pool> = { <item>, ... } } }
--     <Pool> in { "Treasure", "Regular", "Bore", "Burrow" } (server grant order)
--     <item> = { id = <itemId>, n = "English Name", w = <weight>, rank = <req> }
--       w    = dig weight (higher = more likely; digcalc: q = min(1, w/(1000*mu)))
--       rank = dig-rank requirement, index into `ranks` below (0 = Amateur)
--   cond = the conditional Regular-pool rule tables (maps + gates), below.
--   ranks = the 0..10 dig-rank ladder (index = rank number).

return {

-- The dig-rank ladder (0..10 = the CatsEye craftRank range for Digging),
-- matching the server's first-dig zone cooldown clamp(60 - 5*rank, 10, 60)s:
-- Amateur(0)=60s .. Adept(8)=20s, Veteran(9)=15s, Expert(10)=10s (the 10s floor
-- makes rank 10 the effective max). Rock/ore gates reference it by index
-- (Novice = 3, Craftsman = 6). Loot rankReq itself never exceeds Adept(8), so
-- ranks 9/10 only sharpen the rank LABEL + the timing detection (issue #100).
ranks = {
  [0] = "Amateur",
  [1] = "Recruit",
  [2] = "Initiate",
  [3] = "Novice",
  [4] = "Apprentice",
  [5] = "Journeyman",
  [6] = "Craftsman",
  [7] = "Artisan",
  [8] = "Adept",
  [9] = "Veteran",
  [10] = "Expert",
},

